KUALA LUMPUR: Mulai 21 Julai ini, ahli Kumpulan Wang Simpanan Pekerja (KWSP) boleh menggunakan simpanan dari Akaun Dua untuk menyelesaikan baki pinjaman pendidikan mereka.
Pengeluaran itu tidak lagi terhad kepada tarikh kuatkuasa perjanjian pinjaman pendidikan masing-masing.
Timbalan Ketua Pegawai Eksekutif (Operasi) KWSP, Datuk Mohd Naim Daruwish, berkata penambahbaikan polisi itu memanfaatkan 70,000 ahli yang belum menyelesaikan baki pinjaman pendidikan.
Beliau berkata, ia dilakukan selepas mengambil kira maklum balas ahli yang mengalami kesukaran mengurang atau menyelesaikan baki pinjaman pendidikan menggunakan simpanan mereka.
"Pihak KWSP sentiasa memberikan pengalaman positif kepada ahli dan berusaha melakukan penambahbaikan dari semasa ke semasa," kata agensi itu dalam kenyataan.
Dalam pada itu, Mohd Naim berkata syarat baharu itu terbuka kepada semua tarikh kuatkuasa pinjaman yang tertakluk kepada syarat semasa pengeluaran akaun kedua ketika ini.
Katanya, ia masing-masing menggantikan syarat semasa untuk pembiayaan pengajian anak ahli di peringkat ijazah dan ke atas serta setaranya pada 1 April 2000; pembiayaan pengajian ahli peringkat diploma dan ke atas serta setaranya pada 2 Januari 2001; dan pembiayaan pengajian ahli dan anak di peringkat diploma dan ke atas atau setaranya pada 17 Januari 2006.
2017  BH Online | New Straits Times Press (M) Berhad (4485-H) | Hak Cipta Terpelihara
PERMODALAN Nasional Bhd (PNB) announced an income distribution of 4.50 sen per unit, 4.25 sen per unit and 5.15 sen per unit for all three funds under the Amanah Saham Gemilang (ASG), namely ASG-Pendidikan, ASG-Kesihatan and ASG-Persaraan (Funds) for the financial year ended March 31, 2017.
According to Tan Sri Abdul Wahid Omar, group chairman of PNB, The performance of the funds for the current financial year had been affected by the challenging economic landscape, especially on the Malaysian domestic equity market pressured by global geopolitical events, low commodity prices and a prolonged depreciation of the ringgit.
The unfavourable market environment had a considerable impact on the funds as domestic equities constitute a significant portion the funds portfolio of investments.
Despite the bearish performance of the market throughout the most part of the recent financial year, the funds had consistently outperformed its benchmark over the past ten years. The funds had also declared competitive income distribution, ranging from 4.25 sen to 7.30 sen per unit, since inception in March 2003.
For the year under review, the units in circulation (UIC) of the funds increased by 64.3% to a total of 3.1 billion units. This reflects the attractiveness of the funds as investors look for low volatility and medium risks investments with competitive income distribution. PNB also believes that a significant portion of the funds subscription is attributed to the increased expectation of market improvements as investors believe that the market performance is on the uptrend can take advantage of the low prices over the recent years in the hope of riding the market recovery.
Moving forward
Since the start of the year, global economic growth has been showing positive improvements, favorably impacting the local market. In addition, PNB is in the midst of improving the fundamentals of its investee companies in its effort to improve the corporate earnings of its domestic equities.
As quoted by Wahid, Despite some risks coming from the external side, Malaysias 2017 economic outlook remains broadly favourable, reflecting a well-diversified economy and accommodative government policies.
The stable outlook of the ringgit, positive foreign inflows as well as stability of the market are some of the major factors driving the domestic stock markets positive performance to date. As at March 31, 2017, FBM KLCI closed at 1,745.75 points, a rise of 6.3% from 1,636.94 points at the start of the year, he added.
As at March 2017, more than of the funds assets are invested in domestic equities, supported by investments in fixed income and money market instruments.
ASG was launched on March 17, 2003 with the aim of providing investment returns that meet three main financial planning objectives, namely Pendidikan (education); Kesihatan (health) and Persaraan (retirement).
Therefore, investors are encouraged to hold their investment for medium to long-term horizon to allow the funds to generate reasonable long-term growth and returns, in meeting its respective objectives.
MIDF head of research Zulkifli Hamzah expected the local stock market to perform significantly better in 2017 after three years of lackluster performance.
One of the main drivers of the market is the return of foreign funds as several global investment banks turned positive towards Malaysian equity, he said.
He said the bullish outlook on Malaysian market was supported by stronger economic growth target, undervalued ringgit and various value-accretive corporate exercises.
The local stock market has gained more than 6.8% since the beginning of the year.
PNB said it expected funds under ASG to continue to perform better than its benchmark, which the firm has successfully fulfilled in the last 10 years.
